Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Creighton   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Creighton","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: habitational name from Crichton, near Edinburgh, first recorded <i>c.</i> 1128 in the form <i>Crectune</i>, in 1287 as <i>Crecton</i>, and in 1360 as <i>Creychtona</i>. The name is probably an early hybrid compound of Old Welsh <i>creic</i> ‘rock’ + Older Scots <i>tun</i> ‘farm, settlement’ (Old English <i>tūn</i>). In Ireland and Britain, this form of the name is now found chiefly in northern Ireland; the more usual Scottish forms are   Crichton   and   Crighton  .","Irish: sometimes used for Gaelic <b>Ó Creacháin</b> or <b>Ó Criocháin</b> (see   Crehan  ).","English: habitational name from Creighton in Staffordshire, named with Celtic <i>creig</i> ‘rock’ + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’."]}]},{"name":"Thurstan","type":"FIRST","meanings":["An old name. The same as the Old and Middle High German names Turstan, Thurstan, Turstein, signifying 'Thor's stone;' figuratively 'Thor's defence;' from Anglo-Saxon stdn, Old Norman steinn. It is found Latinised Turstanus. Thor is found in many old names, as Thurgar, Thurgood, Thurkettle, Thurkle, Thurtle."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thurstan de Crichton was born about 1100, in Pathhead, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Thurstan De Brastenburg, was 41 and his mother, Alice De Montfort, was 51. He had at least 1 son with Lady Thurstan de Crichton. He died about 1140, in his hometown, at the age of 42."},"et":{"Abt 1100–Abt 1140":"umbes 1100–umbes 1140","1100–1140":"1100–1140","1100–Female":"1100–Surnud","1140–1183":"1140–1183","1060–Male":"1060–Surnud","1050–1091":"1050–1091","1091":"1091","Abt 1140":"umbes 1140","Abt 1100":"umbes 1100","1100":"1100","1140":"1140","1183":"1183","1050":"1050","1060":"1060","Pathhead, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Pathhead, Midlothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1100–Abt 1140":"noin 1100–noin 1140","1100–1140":"11